introduction.p:
      In this section we discuss subspaces of \R^n.  A subspace turns out to be exactly the same thing as a span, except we dont have a particular set of spanning vectors in mind.  This change in perspective is quite useful, as it is easy to produce subspaces that are not obviously spans.  For example, the solution set of the equation x + 3y + z = 0 is a span because the equation is homogeneous, but we would have to compute the parametric vector form in order to write it as a span.


\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz, z={(0cm,0.8cm)}, scale=.75]
  \def\v{(2,-1,1)}
  \def\w{(1,0,-1)}

  \node[coordinate] (X) at \v {};
  \node[coordinate] (Y) at \w {};

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), transformxy]
    \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-1,-1.5) rectangle (1,1.5);
    \draw[step=.5cm, seq4!50, very thin] (-1,-1.5) grid (1,1.5);
  \end{scope}

  \node[seq4, resetxy, right] at (3.5, 0) {$x+3y+z=0$};

  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}


      (A subspace also turns out to be the same thing as the solution set of a homogeneous system of equations.)

subsection.p:
For instance, the unit circle
C = \bigl\{ (x,y)\text{ in }\R^2 \bigm| x^2 + y^2 = 1 \bigr\}
is a subset of \R^2.

example.p:
A line L through the origin is a subspace.

  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \draw[seq4] (-3,-1) -- (3,1);
    \draw[vector] (0,0) -- (1,1/3);
    \point at (0,0);
    \node[seq4] at (0,.5) {$L$};
  \end{tikzpicture}

      Indeed, L contains zero, and is easily seen to be closed under addition and scalar multiplication.

A plane P through the origin is a subspace.

  \begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz]
    \def\v{(-1,2,1)}
    \def\w{(0,1,-1)}

    \node[coordinate] (X) at \v {};
    \node[coordinate] (Y) at \w {};

    \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), transformxy]
      \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-1,-1) rectangle (1,1);
      \draw[step=.5cm, seq4!50, very thin] (-1,-1) grid (1,1);
    \end{scope}

    \draw[vector] (0,0,0) -- ($.5*(X)$);
    \draw[vector] (0,0,0) -- ($.5*(Y)$);

    \point at (0,0,0);
    \node[x=(X),y=(Y),seq4] at (.2,-1.4) {$P$};
  \end{tikzpicture}

      Indeed, P contains zero; the sum of two vectors in P is also in P; and any scalar multiple of a vector in P is also in P.

A line L (or any other subset) that does not contain the origin is not a subspace.  It fails the first defining property: every subspace contains the origin by definition.

  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \draw[seq4] (-3,-1) -- (3,1);
    \point at (0,-.5);
    \point[red] at (0,-.5);
  \end{tikzpicture}

The unit circle C is not a subspace.  It fails all three defining properties: it does not contain the origin, it is not closed under addition, and it is not closed under scalar multiplication.  In the picture, one red vector is the sum of the two black vectors (which are contained in C), and the other is a scalar multiple of a black vector.

  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \draw[seq4] (0,0) circle [radius=2cm];
    \draw[vector,red] (0,0) -- (2.5,0);
    \draw[vector] (0,0) -- (0,2);
    \draw[vector] (0,0) -- (2,0);
    \draw[vector,red] (0,0) -- (2,2);
    \point at (0,0);
    \point[red] at (0,0);
  \end{tikzpicture}

The first quadrant in \R^2 is not a subspace.  It contains the origin and is closed under addition, but it is not closed under scalar multiplication (by negative numbers).

  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \fill[seq4!20] (0,0) rectangle (2,2);
    \draw[->] (-2,0) -- (2,0);
    \draw[->] (0,-2) -- (0,2);
    \draw[vector] (0,0) -- (1,1);
    \draw[vector,red] (0,0) -- (-1,-1);
    \point at (0,0);
  \end{tikzpicture}

The union of a line and a plane in \R^3 is not a subspace.  It contains the origin and is closed under scalar multiplication, but it is not closed under addition: the sum of a vector on the line and a vector on the plane is not contained in the line or in the plane.

  \begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz]
    \path[clip, resetxy] (-4,-2) rectangle (4,2);

    \draw[seq4] (-2,-1,-4) -- (0,0,0);

    \begin{scope}[transformxy]
      \fill[seq4!20, semitransparent] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (1.5,1.5);
      \draw[step=.5cm, grid lines] (-1.5,-1.5) grid (1.5,1.5);
    \end{scope}

    \draw[seq4] (2,1,4) -- (0,0,0);

    \draw[vector] (0,0,0) -- (.6,.3,1.2);
    \draw[vector] (0,0,0) -- (0,1,0);
    \draw[vector,red] (0,0,0) -- (.6,1.3,1.2);

    \point at (0,0,0);

  \end{tikzpicture}

bluebox.p:
A subset of \R^n is any collection of vectors whatsoever.  For instance, the unit circle
C = \bigl\{ (x,y)\text{ in }\R^2 \bigm| x^2 + y^2 = 1 \bigr\}
is a subset of \R^2, but it is not a subspace.  In fact, all of the non-examples above are still subsets of \R^n.  A subspace is a subset that happens to satisfy the three additional defining properties.

solution.p:
        Since V satisfies all three defining properties, it is a subspace.
        In fact, it is the line through the origin with slope 2/3.

\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw[help lines] (-3, -3) grid (3, 3);
  \draw[seq4] (-3,-2) -- (3,2);
  \point at (0,0);
  \node[seq4] at (1.5,.7) {$V$};
\end{tikzpicture}

Next we check the second property.  It turns out that V is not closed under addition; to verify this, we must show that there exists some vectors u,v in V such that u+v is not contained in V.  The easiest way to do so is to produce examples of such vectors.  We can take u={1\choose 0} and v={0\choose 1}; these are contained in V because the products of their coordinates are zero, but
\vec{1 0} + \vec{0 1} = \vec{1 1}
is not contained in V because 1\cdot 1\neq 0.

          Since V does not satisfy the second property (it is not closed under addition), we conclude that V is not a subspace.  Indeed, it is the union of the two coordinate axes, which is not a span.

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
  \draw[grid lines, step=.25] (-1,-1) grid (1,1);
  \draw[seq4, <->, thick] (-1,0) -- (1,0);
  \draw[seq4, <->, thick] (0,-1) -- (0,1);
  \node[seq4] at (.25,.25) {$V$};
\end{tikzpicture}

          The column space is the span of the columns of A:
          \Col(A) = \Span\left\{\vec{1 1 1},\;\vec{1 1 1}\right\}
          = \Span\left\{\vec{1 1 1}\right\}.

          This is a line in \R^3.

\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz, x={(-.3cm,-.4cm)}, z={(0cm,1cm)}]
  \path[clip, resetxy] (-4,-2) rectangle (4,2);

  \draw[seq4] (-4,-4,-4) -- (0,0,0);
   \begin{scope}[transformxy]
    \fill[white, semitransparent] (-1.5,-1.5) rectangle (1.5,1.5);
    \draw[step=1cm, grid lines] (-1.5,-1.5) grid (1.5,1.5);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[seq4] (4,4,4) -- (0,0,0);
  \draw[vector] (0,0,0) -- (1,1,1);
  \draw[densely dotted] (1,1,0) -- (1,1,1);
  \node[resetxy,seq4,below right] at (1.5,1.5) {$\Col(A)$};
  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

          The null space is the solution set of the homogeneous system Ax=0.  To compute this, we need to row reduce A.  Its reduced row echelon form is
          \mat{1 1; 0 0; 0 0}.
          This gives the equation x+y=0, or
          \syseq{x = -y; y = y}
          \quad\xrightarrow{\text{parametric vector form}}\quad
          \vec{x y} = y\vec{-1 1}.

          Hence the null space is \Span\bigl\{{-1\choose 1}\bigr\}, which is a line in \R^2.

\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw[grid lines] (-3,-3) grid (3,3);
  \draw[seq4] (3,-3) -- (-3,3);
  \draw[vector] (0,0) -- (-1,1);
  \point at (0,0);
  \node[seq4,fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (-.7,2) {$\Nul(A)$};
\end{tikzpicture}

specialcase.p:
Null spaceis a solution set
Solution setof a homogeneous system is a null space
The null space of a matrix is the solution set of a homogeneous system of equations.  For example, the null space of the matrix

  A = \mat{1 7 2; -2 1 3; 4 -2 -3}

is the solution set of Ax=0, i.e., the solution set of the system of equations

  \syseq{
  x + 7y + 2z = 0;
  -2x + y + 3z = 0;
  4x - 2y - 3z = 0\rlap.
  }

Conversely, the solution set of any homogeneous system of equations is precisely the null space of the corresponding coefficient matrix.
